<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="4.4.1">Jekyll</generator><link href="http://localhost:4000/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="http://localhost:4000/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2026-07-12T21:09:49+00:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/feed.xml</id><title type="html">=][=</title><subtitle>A hobby blog covering Warhammer, painting, conversions, and grimdark projects.</subtitle><entry><title type="html">Rest in Peace: John Blanche</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/2026/07/08/rip-john-blanche.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Rest in Peace: John Blanche" /><published>2026-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2026-07-08T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/2026/07/08/rip-john-blanche</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/2026/07/08/rip-john-blanche.html"><![CDATA[<blockquote>
  <p>The Bell of Lost Souls will now ring 40,000 times.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>There are no words to truly convey the impact that John Blanche had on the world of Warhammer and miniature painting. His art, commonly referred to by the community as “Blanchitsu”, pioneered the “grim dark” style that defined the early editions of Warhammer 40,000, and would be the pillar upon which everything else was built. It’s a reductive method of painting that uses a fairly sparse colour pallete, mostly focusing on earthy tones such as reds, oranges, and browns, but blended in a way that instantly tells a story. It’s an instantly recognisable style, especially for those of us who have been around the hobby for a long time. For some of us his art was what drew us in in the first place.</p>

<p>Without knowing it, I’ve been exposed to John’s art since my childhood, all the early edition 40k box arts are John’s pieces. The bright red of the Blood Angels on the Second edition box, to the iconic Black Templars art used on the box of the Third edition, his iconic depiction of The Emperor of Mankind, the iconic Sister of Battle stood on the hill with her foot on a skull, his incredible work on the Mordheim rulebook… the list just goes on and on.</p>

<p>John Blanche will forever live on through his art and the inspiration he has provided for others. A true legend.</p>

<hr />

<p><img src="/assets/img/blanche-tech-priest.png" alt="Rest in Peace John Blanche" /></p>]]></content><author><name></name></author><category term="grimdark" /><category term="blanchitsu" /><category term="warhammer" /><summary type="html"><![CDATA[A short tribute to painting legend John Blanche, who passed away this year.]]></summary><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="http://localhost:4000/assets/img/blanche1.jpg" /><media:content medium="image" url="http://localhost:4000/assets/img/blanche1.jpg" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" /></entry><entry><title type="html">The Ferrifractor Cartel</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/2026/03/01/ferrifractor-cartel.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="The Ferrifractor Cartel" /><published>2026-03-01T00:00:00+00:00</published><updated>2026-03-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/2026/03/01/ferrifractor-cartel</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/2026/03/01/ferrifractor-cartel.html"><![CDATA[<p><img src="/assets/img/blanche1.jpg" alt="&quot;Test&quot;" /></p>

